  "summary": "Yuki and Yuzu engage in a philosophical discussion regarding the nature of darkness and light. Yuki suggests that even absolute darkness eventually fades to purple, referencing the Snow Queen Selene, who found peace in a world without light. Yuzu remarks on the melancholy of the night and the inability of flowers to bloom in the lightless city of Xiangyuan. Yuzu further suggests that the \"white raven\" is no longer a raven and warns the narrator not to dwell on the matter before walking away.\n\nLater, the narrator, Kouki, finds Mizuho sitting in the courtyard of the Inari household, which resembles a small botanical garden. Wearing a white dress, a pale Mizuho describes a sense of something \"terrifying\" within the city. She suffers a coughing fit, attributing her poor health to the changing seasons. Mizuho expresses deep trust in Mr. Kimitsuki, whom she compares to a god, believing he will rid the household of its terrors. Kouki attempts to encourage her, suggesting that trust brings redemption.\n\nAs Kouki leaves, he encounters Mukae, who mocks his gentlemanly behavior. Kouki expresses concern that Mizuho appears to be on the brink of death. Mukae and Muto then discuss the underlying reasons for Mizuho's condition, revealing that she is the daughter of a mistress. Muto explains that the Kaga family only recently acknowledged Kaguya, following a relationship twenty years ago involving Kanou and a woman he nearly ran away with.",
